newsitem.title: CHINA: Shanghai soybeans end down on long liquidation.
newsitem.headline: Shanghai soybeans end down on long liquidation.

text.p: Shanghai soybean futures ended down on Tuesday due to long liquidation with the approach of the Chinese lunar new year holiday, traders said.
The key January 1997 contract ended at an intra-day high of 3,180 yuan ($383) per tonne, losing 20 yuan. It opened at a low of 3,170.
March fell five to 3,095, May 70 to 3,100, July 60 to 3,110 and November 10 to 3,350. September did not trade.
Combined volume rose to 16,200 tonnes from 10,400.
"Investors are eager to liquidate their positions with the approach of the 16-day long holiday," one trader said.
The soybeans market will close from February 3 to February 14 over the Chinese lunar new year holiday with trading resuming on February 17.
Analysts expect soybeans to continue to face liquidation in the short term but they said that it was not likely to fall sharply.
